  <static seed="1304" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/RationalFunctions/reduceRationalFunction10.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify the function formula, and if applicable, write the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ H(y) = {\frac{y+4}{y^{2}-6y-40}} }</m></p>
<p>Reduced <m>H(y)=</m> <fillin characters="19" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{1}{y-10}, y\ne -4</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simplify the expression, we first factor both the numerator and denominator, and then cancel common factors.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   H(y) \amp = {\frac{y+4}{y^{2}-6y-40}} \\
                 \amp = \frac{{y+4}}{{\left(y+4\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-10\right)}} \\
                 \amp = {\frac{1}{y-10}, y\ne -4}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Since the factor <m>y+4</m> was canceled, the domain condition lost during the reduction is <m>y \ne -4</m>.</p>
</solution>
